Java modules, the sixty-second tour.

Java nine introduced the java platform module system, often abbreviated J-P-M-S. A module is a named, versioned bundle of packages that explicitly declares two things: which of its packages it exports to the outside world, and which other modules it requires to function. You describe a module in a special file at the root of your sources, called module-info-dot-java. Inside it, you write requires clauses to depend on other modules, both java-development-kit modules and library modules, and exports clauses to make specific packages visible to consumers. Any package you do not list stays module-private, completely invisible from outside the module.

Now, here is the honest, practical framing. Most application code, and especially Spring Boot services, does not use the module system directly. Spring Boot still ships as ordinary classpath jars. The module system really matters in three situations: when you are building a library and you want strong, enforced encapsulation of your internals; when you are using the j-link tool to ship a slimmed-down runtime containing only the modules you actually use; or when you are maintaining the java-development-kit itself. So for your day-to-day Spring work, treat the module system as useful background knowledge rather than something you will reach for constantly.
